children.content:
![Nook Logo](c43d15ff-9259-478c-8a51-efc745715c56)
Welcome to Nook.
===
Nook is a simple Note-taking app with support for [Markdown](https://www.markdownguide.org/getting-started/)  

> Switch to preview mode if you haven't already!
  
It is able to run fully offline using different web APIs / Technologies like [IndexedDB](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/IndexedDB_API), [Origin Private Filesystem](https://developer.chrome.com/articles/origin-private-file-system/) for storage and [Service Workers](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Service_Worker_API/Using_Service_Workers) that cache the needed files for offline use.  
  
- Learn how to [navigate and use Nook](/editor/7a25a158-4d6d-4a5f-818b-9fa2ece98d6d)
- Learn how to [use Markdown](/editor/850afff0-a045-4bd7-af34-bc412d2bbfd5/ea4dea9a-6d31-42dd-b5a4-47c79c485003)
- Learn more about the [tech stack](/explorer/6bc324fd-5e04-431c-9a60-5eae0708ee2f)
  
**Source Code** can be found at [Github](https://github.com/frkri/Nook) under the MIT License. There can you also find instructions for self-hosting and setting up a development environment!

## Try Nook on Mobile
This QR code will ask to import a simple example Bucket.
![Nook QR code](4c94a391-8864-4055-93e1-b1a219a0571c)
Direct URL: [https://nook-dot.vercel.app?import=https://raw.githubusercontent.com/frkri/Nook/master/examples/SimpleExample.json](https://nook-dot.vercel.app?import=https://raw.githubusercontent.com/frkri/Nook/master/examples/SimpleExample.json)

# Nook Usage Guide
Here are some of the ways to navigate and use Nook.

## Basic Navigation
Use either the Back Arrow or the Home Button to navigate between Entries.
Another way to navigate is thru the use of links: [Goto Readme file](/editor/e7a896b0-52da-40e9-a451-804e633345ca)
### Navigation Bar
Use the nav bar to input the path to a file or a folder, just as you would with any other filesystem browser  
> Note: Input is case sensitive and accepts spaces!
**TIP: Type / to focus it, when currently not focused on a input**
### Paths
There are predetermined paths that provide different functions which can be seen in the browser navigation bar:  
- /explorer/(...path)
Browse and manage Notes and Directories (Entries)
- /editor/(...path)
Edit, preview and export Notes

> Each Entry has its own ID which is displayed in the browser navigation bar
Example: **Nook Usage Guide** has currently the ID of **7a25a158-4d6d-4a5f-818b-9fa2ece98d6d**

## Editor
### Hotkeys
Available Combinations:  
- CTRL + Q = Switch between Edit and Preview Modes
- CTRL + S = Quickly Save current Note
- CTRL + E = Export current Note to either Markdown or HTML

> Make sure to enable **hotkeys** from the options menu!
> Can be found top right on the save button
![Nook options menu button](cf77549d-8e07-4076-854e-5ec7a8c83029)

### File Sync across Tabs
On each **save** (either from manual or auto), the editor instance will inform all other editor instances about the changes made and update them. This allows, for example, a split view where one editor instance is used for editing and the other for automatic preview of text.  
The number of editor instances can be seen in the bottom right
![Instance Count](b7bb529e-8abc-476f-a1af-d13435a75682)
> Make sure to enable **broadcast file updates** from the options menu!


### Auto Save
Nook has the ability to autosave changes made to a Note. The time limit before automatically saving the contents of a Note, when not typing, by default is set to 800 milliseconds. This can be modified to fit your needs in the options menu.  
![Nook options menu](38b09c1e-b450-4c52-896f-fb4fd6112d36)
> Make sure to enable **autosave** from the options menu!

### Media Linking 
Use Images within notes using **!**
![Cat Link](8100fe92-c144-4a20-8cd5-d1ea808abf26)
When using local files, it must not start with "https://" as that would mean it is a remote resource and will be loaded as such.
Nook will automatically try to find the file with that ID and load it into this note.  
Other file types can be used within a note, but require the use of HTML elements (video, audio)

## Explorer
#### Drag and Drop
Easily copy files to Nook using **Drag n' Drop**  
Simply drag and drop any File to your browser window and it will be automatically imported as its own file entry  
<!-- Example Video embed -->
Example video:
<video src="3963ac5a-1dd0-4c7e-a48f-0121aa24094b" controls loop autoplay></video>
> Nook's Markdown parser doesn't perform sanitation of HTML, meaning be careful which external files you import!

## Export and Import
Nook can export a single file or everything to a downloadable file (bucket).
A 'bucket' export is a JSON File that contains all the data needed to reconstruct the layout and contents of all of the directories and files
  
Visit the [Home Page](/) and scroll down to see the export and import buttons

**TIP: Use the ?import= to quickly import a remote bucket from a URL**
> Example: [https://nook-dot.vercel.app?import=https://raw.githubusercontent.com/frkri/Nook/master/examples/SimpleExample.json](https://nook-dot.vercel.app?import=https://raw.githubusercontent.com/frkri/Nook/master/examples/SimpleExample.json)

# Markdown Cheat Sheet

Thanks for visiting [The Markdown Guide](https://www.markdownguide.org)!

This Markdown cheat sheet provides a quick overview of all the Markdown syntax elements. It can‚Äôt cover every edge case, so if you need more information about any of these elements, refer to the reference guides for [basic syntax](https://www.markdownguide.org/basic-syntax) and [extended syntax](https://www.markdownguide.org/extended-syntax).

## Basic Syntax

These are the elements outlined in John Gruber‚Äôs original design document. All Markdown applications support these elements.

### Heading

# H1
## H2
### H3

### Bold

**bold text**

### Italic

*italicized text*

### Blockquote

> blockquote

### Ordered List

1. First item
2. Second item
3. Third item

### Unordered List

- First item
- Second item
- Third item

### Code

`code`

### Horizontal Rule

---

### Link

[Markdown Guide](https://www.markdownguide.org)

### Image

![alt text](https://www.markdownguide.org/assets/images/tux.png)

## Extended Syntax

**These elements extend the basic syntax by adding additional features. Not all Markdown applications support these elements.**

### Table

| Syntax | Description |
| ----------- | ----------- |
| Header | Title |
| Paragraph | Text |

### Fenced Code Block

```
{
  "firstName": "John",
  "lastName": "Smith",
  "age": 25
}
```

### Footnote

Here's a sentence with a footnote. [^1]

[^1]: This is the footnote.

### Heading ID

### My Great Heading {#custom-id}

### Definition List

term
: definition

### Strikethrough

~~The world is flat.~~

### Task List

- [x] Write the press release
- [ ] Update the website
- [ ] Contact the media

### Emoji

That is so funny! :joy:

(See also [Copying and Pasting Emoji](https://www.markdownguide.org/extended-syntax/#copying-and-pasting-emoji))

### Highlight

I need to highlight these ==very important words==.

### Subscript

H~2~O

### Superscript

X^2^
